
'''* Article: The political economy of the podcast and the rise of the left entrepreneur. By Joshua Sperber. Ephemera, volume 21(4), 2021. Special issue: Pasts, presents and futures of critical publishing anniversary note'''

URL = http://www.ephemerajournal.org/contribution/political-economy-podcast-and-rise-left-entrepreneur


=Summary=

"There has been no shortage of leftist analyses of our ongoing transformations, but there has been less consideration of the ways in which these transformations have affected leftist analysis itself. Indeed, through the hegemonic expansion of the internet, leftist communication and more specifically critical publishing, which increasingly – and at times exclusively – occurs online, has significantly changed not only in its form but also in its content. Surveying key developments over the past 20 years and their effects on left (i.e. self-described anti-capitalist) online communication can allow us to think about where much critical publishing has recently been, where it is now, and where it is going. This paper specifically addresses left media developments within the United States, although it argues that due to the global structural economic forces underlying these changes it is as likely as not that comparable developments will also emerge elsewhere."


